* In {{ill|Chinese chemical nomenclature|ja|中国語の化合物命名法|12=draft}}, '''Kō (庚)''' is used for '''heptane (ヘプタン)''', '''heptyl groups (ヘプチル基)''', and other compounds containing '''seven carbon atoms'''.
* According to the Five Elements' destructive cycle, '''"Fire conquers Metal" (火剋金)''', meaning metal is subdued by fire. Thus, in traditional beliefs, days of '''Kō during the peak fire season of summer''' are considered inauspicious. These three Kō days in summer are called '''Sanpuku (三伏)'''.
* Its counterpart in the '''Ten Stems polarity''' is '''Otsu (乙)'''.
* '''Eho (恵方, auspicious direction)''' for '''Kō years''' is '''west-southwest, slightly west (255°).'''

