* In the {{ill|Gregorian calendar|1=Gregorian calendar|2=ja|3=グレゴリオ暦|4=fr|5=Calendrier grégorien|6=de|7=Gregorianischer Kalender|8=tl|9=Kalendaryong Gregoryano|10=ru|11=Григорианский календарь|ja|西暦|1=Common Era|2=ja|3=西暦|4=zh|5=公元|6=es|7=Era común|8=nl|9=Gangbare jaartelling|10=simple|11=Common Era|12=draft}} and the {{ill|Japanese Imperial Year|ja|神武天皇即位紀元|1=Japanese imperial year|12=draft}}, years ending in '''0''' (i.e., multiples of '''10''') correspond to '''Kō years (庚の年)'''. Another name for such years is '''Jōshō (上章)'''.<ref>{{Cite web |title=古代天干地支的别称及解释_书法欣赏_词典网 |url=https://www.cidianwang.com/shufazuopin/jiaocheng/932596.htm |website=www.cidianwang.com |access-date=2024-03-08}}</ref>.
* In {{ill|Chinese chemical nomenclature|ja|中国語の化合物命名法|12=draft}}, '''Kō (庚)''' is used for '''heptane (ヘプタン)''', '''heptyl groups (ヘプチル基)''', and other compounds containing '''seven carbon atoms'''.
* According to the Five Elements' destructive cycle, '''"Fire conquers Metal" (火剋金)''', meaning metal is subdued by fire. Thus, in traditional beliefs, days of '''Kō during the peak fire season of summer''' are considered inauspicious. These three Kō days in summer are called '''Sanpuku (三伏)'''.
* Its counterpart in the '''Ten Stems polarity''' is '''Otsu (乙)'''.
* '''Eho (恵方, auspicious direction)''' for '''Kō years''' is '''west-southwest, slightly west (255°).'''

