== Overview ==  

* The kanji '''庚''' is a {{ill|pictogram|ja|象形文字|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/pictogram|comment=changed title based on wikidata|1=Hieroglyph|qid=Q193762}} representing a type of musical instrument.<ref>{{Citation| author=Ji Xusheng (季旭昇)| year=2014| title=説文新証| location=Taipei| publisher=芸文印書館| isbn=978-957-520-168-5| page=965|qq=}}</ref><ref>{{Citation| author=Lin Zhiqiang et al. (林志強等)| year=2017| title=《文源》評注| location=Beijing| publisher=中国社会科学出版社| isbn=978-7-5203-0419-1| page=97|qq=}}</ref><ref>{{Citation| author=Ge Liang (葛亮)| year=2022| title=漢字再発現――従旧識到新知| location=Shanghai| publisher=上海書画出版社| isbn=978-7-5479-2884-4| pages=106–9|qq=}}</ref> The use of this character to represent the seventh stem is due to {{ill|phonetic loan|ja|仮借|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/phonetic loan|1=Loangraph|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q10888485}}.
* In the {{ill|Common Era|en|Common Era|qid=Q208141|lt=Common Era|1=Common Era}} and the {{ill|Japanese imperial year|en|Japanese imperial year|qid=Q1209728|lt=Japanese imperial year|1=Japanese imperial year}}, years ending in '''0''' (i.e., multiples of '''10''') correspond to '''Kō years (庚の年)'''. Another name for such years is '''Jōshō (上章)'''.<ref>{{Cite web |title=古代天干地支的别称及解释_书法欣赏_词典网 |url=https://www.cidianwang.com/shufazuopin/jiaocheng/932596.htm |website=www.cidianwang.com |access-date=2024-03-08|qq=}}</ref>.
* In {{ill|Chinese chemical nomenclature|ja|中国語の化合物命名法|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chinese chemical nomenclature|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, '''Kō (庚)''' is used for '''heptane (ヘプタン)''', '''heptyl groups (ヘプチル基)''', and other compounds containing '''seven carbon atoms'''.
* According to the Five Elements' destructive cycle, '''"Fire conquers Metal" (火剋金)''', meaning metal is subdued by fire. Thus, in traditional beliefs, days of '''Kō during the peak fire season of summer''' are considered inauspicious. These three Kō days in summer are called '''Sanpuku (三伏)'''.
* Its counterpart in the '''Ten Stems polarity''' is '''Otsu (乙)'''.
* '''Eho (恵方, auspicious direction)''' for '''Kō years''' is '''west-southwest, slightly west (255°).'''

